Problem 1

The file banking.txt attached to this assignment provides data acquired from banking and census records for different zip codes in the bank’s current market. Such information can be useful in targeting advertising for new customers or for choosing locations for branch offices.

The data show:
  • median age of the population (AGE)
  • median income (INCOME) in $
  • average bank balance (BALANCE) in $
  • median years of education (EDUCATION)

Use R to compute the analysis below. All the functions are in the code for that we covered in class so far and in the exercises. This is the first assignment, and for many of you it may be the first time you use R. So if you run into an error, post a message on the discussion board or contact me. Make sure to include your code in the message.

Problem 4

A survey of IS managers was used to predict the yearly salary of beginning programmer analysts in a metropolitan area. Managers specified their standard salary (SALARY) in $1000 for a beginning programmer/analyst, the number of employees (NUMEMPL) in the firm’s information processing staff, the firm’s gross profit margin (MARGIN) in cents per dollar of sales and the firm’s information processing cost (IPCOST) as a percentage of total administrative costs.

We’ll fit a regression model to evaluate if starting salaries are affected by either the number of IS employees, IP costs and margin profits. The data is in salary_IS.txt.

# import text file with header
sal <- read.table("../Data/salary_IS.txt", header = TRUE)

1)

#
numempl_plot <- ggplot(sal, aes(x=numempl, y=salary)) + 
                geom_point() +
                geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE) +
                labs(title="Salary according to the \n Number of Employees",
                     x="Number of Employees", y = "Salary (US Dollars per $1,000)") +
                # move the title text to the middle
                theme(plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5)) +
                theme(text = element_text(size = 7))  +
                theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 7))

Regression Model 2)

# regression model
salary_model <- lm(salary ~ numempl + margin + ipcost, data = sal)
# show the theoretical model
equatiomatic::extract_eq(salary_model)

\[ \operatorname{salary} = \alpha + \beta_{1}(\operatorname{numempl}) + \beta_{2}(\operatorname{margin}) + \beta_{3}(\operatorname{ipcost}) + \epsilon \]

# display the actual coefficients
equatiomatic::extract_eq(salary_model, use_coefs = TRUE)

\[ \operatorname{\widehat{salary}} = 25.9 + 0(\operatorname{numempl}) + 0.09(\operatorname{margin}) + 0.21(\operatorname{ipcost}) \]

equatiomatic::extract_eq(new_salary_model, use_coefs = TRUE)

Analyze the Goodness of fit 6)

#residuals vs fitted values plot
residual_plot <-  ggplot(new_salary_model, aes(x = .fitted, y = .resid)) +
                  geom_point() +
                  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, col = "red") +
                  labs(title="Fitted vs Residuals Plot",
                    x = "Fitted Values", 
                    y = "Residual") +
                  # move the title text to the middle
                  theme(plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5))  +
                  theme(text = element_text(size = 7))  +
                  theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 7))

#residuals vs margin variable
marginr_plot <- ggplot(sal, aes(x = margin, y = rstandard(new_salary_model))) +
                geom_point() +
                geom_hline(yintercept = 0, col = "red") +
                labs(title="Margin vs Residuals Plot",
                    x = "Margin(Cents per Dollar Sales)", 
                    y = "Residual") +
                # move the title text to the middle
                theme(plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5))  +
                theme(text = element_text(size = 7))  +
                theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 7))
#residuals vs ipcost variable
ipcostr_plot <- ggplot(sal, aes(x = ipcost, y = rstandard(new_salary_model))) +
                geom_point() +
                geom_hline(yintercept = 0, col = "red") +
                labs(title="IPCost vs Residuals Plot",
                    x = "Margin(Cents per Dollar Sales)", 
                    y = "Residual") +
                # move the title text to the middle
                theme(plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5))  +
                theme(text = element_text(size = 7))  +
                theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 7))


#create Q-Q plot
qq_plot <-  ggplot(new_salary_model, aes(sample=rstandard(new_salary_model))) +
            stat_qq(size=1.5, color='blue') + 
            stat_qq_line(col = "red") +
            labs(title="Normal Q-Q Plot",
              x = "Theoretical Quantiles", 
              y = "Sample Quantiles") +
            # move the title text to the middle
            theme(plot.title=element_text(hjust=0.5))  +
            theme(text = element_text(size = 7))  +
            theme(axis.title = element_text(size = 7))


# combine all four plots
residualt_plot <-  ggarrange(residual_plot, marginr_plot, ipcostr_plot,qq_plot,
